+\smallskip
+\noindent\emph{Scope of (H5): class~$\mathbf{G}$ versus
+non-class-$\mathbf{G}$ landscape.}
+Axiom~\textbf{(H5)} is realised on the nose by class~$\mathbf{G}$
+primitive-coproduct algebras (Heisenberg, lattice at integer level,
+$\beta\gamma$ before Sugawara substitute); for these the
+involutive sign map $S(J) = -J$ is a chain-level antipode and
+Heisenberg (Example~\ref{ex:heisenberg-bialgebra}) is the prototype.
+For non-class-$\mathbf{G}$ families with Miura-type nonlinearities,
+a chain-level antipode does \emph{not} exist: the classical Yangian
+antipode $S(T(u)) = T(u)^{-1}$ does not lift to a vertex-algebraic
+antipode on $\cW_{1+\infty}[\Psi]$ by two independent obstructions
+(OPE quartic pole $S(T)_{(3)}S(T) = c/2 + 2(\Psi{-}1)(\Psi{-}2)$ at
+generic~$\Psi$, and a universal Hopf-axiom residual
+$-\frac{\Psi-1}{z^2} + z\,J$ in the convolution
+$m_z \circ (S \otimes \mathrm{id}) \circ \Delta_z$).  This is the
+proved negative of Vol~I, Proposition
+\textup{\texttt{prop:w-infty-antipode-obstruction}}
+(\texttt{chapters/theory/ordered\_associative\_chiral\_kd.tex}).
+Consequently, the object that concrete CY quantum groups
+(toroidal, Yangian, affine BPS) inhabit is an
+$E_1$-chiral bialgebra (axioms \textbf{(H1)--(H4)}), not an
+$E_1$-chiral Hopf algebra.  The present chapter retains the
+Hopf-axiom definition for the class~$\mathbf{G}$ prototype and for
+naming the obstruction target; the rest of the volume consistently
+treats the chiral object as a bialgebra and invokes the antipode
+only on the classical point-value fibre via the Drinfeld double
+programme (Vol~II, Conjecture
+\textup{\texttt{conj:drinfeld-double-e1-construction}}
+in \texttt{chapters/connections/ordered\_associative\_chiral\_kd\_frontier.tex}).
 \end{remark}
 
